<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-158-646  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 158 646.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  Feb 16 1989 v15 n4 p15(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>In conversation. (John Wyatt of James Martin Associates)(interview)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Campbell, Gordon.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>John L. Wyatt, executive vice president of James Martin AssociatesInc, a leading information technology consulting firm, says thatbusiness objectives are the most stable foundation on which tobuild an information system.andP;  User needs, which are the mostcommon foundation, are too unstable to build a system that willremain effective in the long term.andP;  User needs often change beforesystems are completed, resulting in user unrest and an ineffectiveinformation strategy.andP;  Wyatt believes that the scarcity of CASE(computer-aided software engineering) implementations creates asituation that requires extreme care.andP;  CASE should not beoverlooked, but those installing CASE tools must do so withrealistic expectations.andP;  Wyatt says that reverse engineering is aviable, although difficult, way to extract value from existingsystems.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   James Martin Associates (UK) Ltd. (officials and employees).andO;Topic:     InterviewConsultantsInformation SystemsTurnkey Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   John L. Wyatt. (portrait)Person:    Wyatt, John L. (interviews).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>